ds on Earth. He ventures across the Solar System to consider how the planets can act to produce climate change, even global disaster. Kaler shows how Jupiter's gravity can throw asteroids toward potentially devastating collision with Earth, and how even our whole Galaxy might hurl comet storms at us. He then takes us into deepest space to describe the cosmic rays launched at us from exploding stars, and considers not just how these exploders might harm us, but how they also join together in the creation of stars and how they serve to populate the Universe with the very building blocks of life.Informative and entertaining, Heaven's Touch reveals how intimately connected we really are with the dynamic Universe in which we live.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aAstronomyvPopular works. 0aCometsvPopular works. 0aCosmic raysvPopular works. 0aLifexOriginvPopular works. 0aStarsvPopular works. 0aSupernovaevPopular works. 7aSCIENCE / Astronomy.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781400833450zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400833450423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781400833450/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MTPY  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MTPY  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK